\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0 An honor system was set up where each side would take care of housing its own soldiers who had been designated as being on parole, meaning they would not fight in combat unless they were formally exchanged. The Confederates did not set up parole camps; they let their men go home and expected them to return to duty once officially exchanged. Parole camps were set up by the Union Army for its own soldiers who had been captured by the Confederacy, and then released on the condition that they would honor the terms and conditions of their parole.}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parole_camp#cite_note-2"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0\super [}}{\f0\fs24\b0\ul\ulc0\super\cf4 2]}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 In 1862, a parole camp was established in\~}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Annapolis,_Maryland"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0 Annapolis, Maryland}}{\f0\fs24\b0 , on the grounds of\~}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/St._John%27s_College_(Annapolis/Santa_Fe)"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0 St. John's College}}{\f0\fs24\b0 ,}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parole_camp#cite_note-ANC-3"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0\super [}}{\f0\fs24\b0\ul\ulc0\super\cf4 3]}{\f0\fs24\b0 \~But this camp soon ran out of space, so two more were soon built in the local area. One was located in nearby\~}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parole,_Maryland"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0 Parole, Maryland}}{\f0\fs24\b0 , which is how the town got its name.}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parole_camp#cite_note-ANC-3"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0\super [}}{\f0\fs24\b0\ul\ulc0\super\cf4 3]}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parole_camp#cite_note-4"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0\super [}}{\f0\fs24\b0\ul\ulc0\super\cf4 4]}{\f0\fs24\b0 \~The resulting influx of soldiers changed the nature of the town, since the soldiers were free to visit the local area as much as they might wish.}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parole_camp#cite_note-book1-5"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0\super [}}{\f0\fs24\b0\ul\ulc0\super\cf4 5]}{\f0\fs24\b0 \~Many soldiers disliked the camp and described it as dirty in their letters home. There were some occasional problems with disorderly conduct by some of the soldiers who were sent there.}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parole_camp#cite_note-book1-5"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0\super [}}{\f0\fs24\b0\ul\ulc0\super\cf4 5]}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 There was a short-lived parole camp in\~}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/West_Chester,_Pennsylvania"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0 West Chester, Pennsylvania}}{\f0\fs24\b0 , known as Camp Elder.}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parole_camp#cite_note-6"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0\super [}}{\f0\fs24\b0\ul\ulc0\super\cf4 6]}{\f0\fs24\b0 \~One paroled soldier, Warren H. Freeman, wrote to his father and said that the parolees in the camp were being guarded by inexperienced members of the Pennsylvania militia, all of whom were fairly lenient in their guard duties, presumably because they were guarding members of their own army}
